	Of all the contractors engaged in various activities at KSC, only United Space Alliance (USA) and Space Gateway Support (SGS) operate processes with regulated chemical at quantities over the threshold amounts.  The first priority of USA is the safe operation of the Space Shuttle while maintaining the safety of the people.  USA¿s Safety and Health plan (SFOC-PA0001) identifies the organizational structure and methodology to ensure the preservation of human and material resources through an orderly, coordinated, and comprehensive institutional safety program.  USA has documented plans in place to manage the risks involved in the day-to-day activities of shuttle processing.  These plans include:  The Space Shuttle Program (SSP) Risk Management Plan which describes the polices, concepts, and approach related to the management of risks in the Space Shuttle Program, the Associate Program Manager (APM) Implementation Plan Blank Book, which provides the structure and direction for the SFOC organizational elements to develop their detailed implementation plans and the Ground Operations Implementation Plan, which documents the implementation of the Risk Management Program into Ground Operations.  This implementation plan defines the processes and procedures for the identification, assessment, handling and communication of risks associated with the Ground Operations function. 

	There are many procedures/mechanisms that are established for the prevention of accidental releases of various hazardous/toxic/regulated chemicals, some of which include:

·	Sumps are used to contain accidental releases of commodities at certain locations;
·	Emergency Firex systems are in place at various locations to be used in the event of an accidental release or spill;
·	Warning Lights/Pa

ging/Fire Alarms/safety showers, etc. are available for use;
·	Safety and Hazardous Clears/Control Areas: Non-essential on-site personnel are not allowed to enter the hazardous areas/operations;
·	Safety Walk-downs before major operations;
·	System Certifications for all pressurized vessels and systems;
·	Continuous training is provided and tracked for workers to assure safe work practices are adhered to. Training is accomplished through hands on classes, videos and on-line training courses; 
·	Preventive Maintenance Procedures;
·	Validation Procedures;
·	Administrative Controls are issued through Engineering Change Notices and other notices;
·	MARSS (Meteorological And Range Safety Support):  Accidental release modeling on call for all hazardous operations;
·	Personal protective equipment requirements are stringent and called out in the maintenance and operations instructions; 
·	USA maintains open and effective communications to ensure safety of operations and people.

	SGS is also committed to personnel and environmental safety, and maintains safety and business programs that ensure compliance with the OSHA PSM rule.  The Fuel Storage Area #1 (FSA-1), run by SGS, has had a long history of safe operation.  Processes and procedures at FSA-1 which ensure compliance include:

·	Test Conductor Program (BOC6403-1366) which includes a pre-operation briefing identifying such things as an overview of the operation, operational hazards, and emergency actions;
·	Operating and maintenance procedures (OMI¿s) as well as engineering instructions;
·	Barricade Plan (BOC4403-1361) which controls (restricts) access during operations, including the process to account for personnel in the event of an evacuation;
·	Area warning lights/horns including the ability to activate an alarm on the Phillips Parkway to close traffic as contained in the Facility Safety Plan (FSP-201);
·	Area monitoring by SGS Safety personnel, Cape Safety, and Environmental Health;
·	The use of drip pans and s

umps to contain accidental releases;
·	Deluge system which can be activated from the test console as well as in the fuel transfer facility;
·	Fire department on standby during operations (as per FSP-201);
·	Hazardous equipment/facility certification program;
·	Personnel protective equipment requirements;
·	Personnel trained/certified in the operation of the equipment and the knowledge of the hazards they work with.

3. Emergency Response Approach

KSC has developed a Comprehensive Emergency Preparedness Plan (CEMP) that is coordinated with all response elements, both on Center and Brevard County Emergency Management. This includes the State Emergency Response Commissions, District VI, Local Emergency Planning Committee.  This plan is the guideline for KSC¿s dynamic emergency preparedness program and is designed to be supplemented by other emergency plans and standard operating procedures required by all internal emergency response elements at KSC.  KSC employs full-time fire, law enforcement, medical, emergency management, and hazardous materials emergency response capability with all required support elements.  KSC¿s policy is to provide "minimum essential" capabilities for responding to the full spectrum of emergencies.  Baseline capabilities are maintained during normal duty circumstances that can be rapidly expanded in the event of an emergency.  

To validate the CEMP, tabletop, functional, and full-scale exercises are conducted on a monthly, quarterly, and annual basis.  The emergency preparedness program is managed by a Certified Emergency Manager with a staff of 6 personnel.  Drills and exercises are developed and conducted by an exercise evaluation team.  Drills and exercises are conducted to validate the Kennedy Documented Procedures (KDPs) listed in the CEMP.  Our KDPs are compliant with ISO 9001 Certification.  

